			<title><![CDATA[November '17 Release Thread]]></title>
			<link>https://www.graffes.com/forums/showthread.php?79883-November-17-Release-Thread&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Tue, 31 Oct 2017 09:18:08 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[This is it. November is the last big month of the year for new releases. While October is overwhelming in quantity, that's largely because historically November is the month of juggernauts no one wants to compete with. This has traditionally meant Call of Duty, but they have had gradually increased...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>This is it. November is the last big month of the year for new releases. While October is overwhelming in quantity, that's largely because historically November is the month of juggernauts no one wants to compete with. This has traditionally meant Call of Duty, but they have had gradually increased competition from EA over the past couple of years.<br />
<br />
Of the two heavyweights this month, I'm going to go out on a limb and say that I think <b>Star Wars Battlefront 2</b> is going to be the overall winner. The previous game was a massive success despite being anemic in content and kind of bland overall. With that success they have the opportunity to massively improve what they created before. They also acknowledged fan demands and created a single player campaign, making it attractive even to people who do not want to play multiplayer.<br />
<br />
The other big contender this month is obviously <b>Call of Duty: WW2</b>. Call of Duty has been huge for awhile now but their star has been waning. When you release a new game every year it can be kind of hard to stay fresh, and they have gradually shifted their focus more and more into science fiction. Call it what you will, a return to form or a last ditch act of desperation, but Call of Duty is now going back to World War 2. They are leaning on this <i>hard</i>, complete with advertisements about thirty-somethings who have moved on in their lives &quot;getting the band back together&quot;. Will it be enough? <br />
<br />
<br />
The only other game this month that really compares to the above two in popularity is <b>Pokemon Ultra Sun and Ultra Moon</b> for the 3DS. Rather than an all new game, this is following Pokemon tradition by expanding the previously released game in a series with new features, pokemon, story, etc. Recycled content or not, people still gobble these up.<br />
<br />
Also worth mentioning this month are <b>Sonic Forces</b>, <b>Need for Speed Payback</b>, and <b>Lego Marvel Super Heroes 2</b>. The last two are fairly self-explanatory, and the only thing I really find worth pointing out about the new Sonic game is that this is the one where you can create your own Sonic character.<br />
<br />
The Switch is getting a ton of ports this month. The most notable being <b>Doom</b> and <b>Skyrim</b>, the PS4 and Vita are sharing another jrpg dungeon crawler in <b>Demon Gaze II</b>, and the PC is getting a port of <b>Nioh</b>, the Japanese themed Dark Soulsy game.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Finally, this month Microsoft releases their <b>Xbox One X</b>. This is Microsoft's answer to all the 900p talk for the past several years when the PS4 was the most powerful console. That is no longer true, and in true Microsoft fashion they let you know by repeating the same buzz words over and over. Power power power power power power power power. :D<br />
<br />
I will be curious to see how this does for them. Sony users will no longer be able to make fun of their performance, but it's also really expensive and Sony has been using their lead to create a kind of insane portfolio of games.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
